Variance and Standard Deviation

March 27, 2020

Section 4.6

Sample Variance and Sample Standard Deviation

Recall that for a dataset of \( \small n \) observations, \( \small x_1, ..., x_n \), that the sample mean is

\[ \bar{x}=\frac{1}{n}\sum\limits_{i=1}^nx_i \]

and the sample variance is

\[ s^2 = \frac{1}{n-1}\sum\limits_{i=1}^n(x_i-\bar{x})^2 \]

with \( s = \sqrt{s^2} \) the sample standard deviation.

The statistics \( s \) and \( s^2 \) represent measures of dispersion of a dataset. Think of \( s \) as the average absolute squared distance of a data value from \( \bar{x} \).

Want to study these concepts in terms of a random variable with a well-defined pmf.

Variance of a Random Variable

Definition.

Let \( \small X \) be a random variable with mean \( \small \mu = E[X] \), such that \( \small \mu < \infty \). Then the variance of X is

\[ \sigma^2 = Var[X] = E[(X-\mu)^2] = \sum\limits_{x}(x-\mu)^2P(X=x) \]

and the standard deviation of X is \( \small \sigma = \sqrt{\sigma^2} \).

Notes.

Can want to write \( \small Var[X] = V[X] \).

Think of \( \small Var[X] \) as the weighted average squared distance of values of \( \small X \) from the mean \( \small \mu \).

\[ Var[X] \geq 0 \text{ for all random variables } \]

\[ Var[X] = E[(X-\mu)^2] \neq E[|X-\mu|] \neq E[X-\mu] \]

Describing Distributions

We are starting to develop statistics that allow us to describe different distributions. The textbook gives an excellent example (4.22) of four distribution where each has \( E[X] = 4 \) but none have the same variance.

Working with Variance

Result.

\[ \begin{aligned} Var[X] = E[X^2]-E[X]^2 = E[X^2] - \mu^2 \end{aligned} \]

Proof.

\[ \begin{aligned} Var[X] &= E[(X-\mu)^2] \\ &= E[X^2 - 2X\mu + \mu^2] \\ &= E[X^2] - 2\mu E[X] + \mu^2 \quad &\#\text{Linear Combination} \\ &= E[X^2] - 2\mu^2 + \mu^2 \quad &\#E[X] = \mu \\ &= E[X^2] - \mu^2 \end{aligned} \]
